cal transport coordination (ensure evacuation vehicles accommodate medical needs)\n- **Elderly woman refusing evacuation**  Police forced evacuation team (legal authority implementation)\n\n**Triage Rationale:** Direct attention to situations that either affect large numbers of people in evacuation context or require coordination between multiple agencies for evacuation purposes. Standard emergencies handled by appropriate specialized services.\n\n---\n\n**Answer 5: Distraction Patterns and Focus Maintenance**\n\n**Identified Distraction Patterns:**\n\n1. **Information Overload Pattern**\n   - Volume increasing from 3-4 updates/hour to 10+ updates/hour\n   - Mix of critical, important, and routine information without clear prioritization\n   - *Focus Strategy*: Establish information filtering criteria and delegate routine monitoring\n\n2. **Scope Creep Pattern**\n   - Non-evacuation emergencies (fires, medical events, infrastructure) demanding attention\n   - *Focus Strategy*: Clear role boundaries - coordinate only when evacuation operations are affected\n\n3. **Media/Political Pressure Pattern**\n   - Press conferences, statistics requests, media access taking coordination time\n   - *Focus Strategy*: Delegate to public information officer, provide hourly updates only\n\n4. **Perfectionism Trap Pattern**\n   - Temptation to solve every problem vs. focusing on primary mission\n   - *Focus Strategy*: Accept that other emergencies will be handled by appropriate services\n\n**Focus Maintenance Strategies:**\n\n**Primary Mission Anchor:**\n- Constant reference to core metric: 4,800  1,200 people still need evacuation before 1 PM\n- All decisions filtered through: "Does this directly help get people out safely?"\n\n**Information Classification System:**\n- **RED (Immediate)**: Affects evacuation timeline or transportation capacity\n- **YELLOW (Important)**: Evacuation-related but can be delegated\n- **GREEN (Monitor)**: Other emergency services handling, awareness only\